Artistic gem added to garden city Suncheon  By Woo Jae yeon  SEOUL Oct 24 Yonhap The southwestern coastal city of Suncheon has added yet another reason for travelers to visit the eco friendly city full of pristine nature and greenery in the coming fall by holding the first eco environmental art festival  At a press briefing Monday the organizers said it will open the Suncheon Bay International Eco Environmental Art Festival SEEAF on Nov 18 which will run through Dec 18 at the Suncheon Bay National Garden a man made massive garden that used to be a natural habitat for more than 500 types of trees and 113 kinds of flowers  The 1 1 million square foot garden was formed in 2013 to stop urban development from damaging the natural landmark Suncheon Bay also a Ramsar site since 2006 With a total of 56 different themed gardens it was designated as the country s first national garden in 2015  Art Director Kim Sung ho of the Suncheon Bay International Eco Environmental Art Festival SEEAF explains the upcoming art event at the Press Center in Seoul on Oct 24 2016 Yonhap  This undated photo shows a bird s eye view of Suncheon Bay Yonhap  The city of Suncheon is already well known for its eco diversity and beautiful garden The city government and the people think now is the time to put more focus on cultivating culture said Kim Young gyu co chairman of the festival The beautiful canvas of the city will surely make artwork installed there shine more beautifully  The organizer invited 57 teams of artists from 24 countries who will bring their paintings art installations and sculptures to the indoor exhibition hall and the outdoor garden under the theme of Voyage into Paradise The theme itself is divided into three parts Paradise Lost Paradise Regained and Paradises of the World  The festival is not about recovering nature but about how to interpret nature through art in the artificial garden Also we want to have a moment to contemplate ecological art said art director Kim Sung ho  Giwa Embracing Land by Lee Seung taek courtesy of the SEEAF Yonhap  Yin and Yang by Kim Ku rim courtesy of the SEEAF Yonhap  Some of the installation artworks will be permanently displayed at the garden even after the festival ends in an effort to make the place more artistically rich  South Korea s celebrated installation artist Lee Seung taek s work Giwa Embracing Land will be among them Giwa are Korean traditional roof tiles He built a pyramid shaped structure with roof tiles fetched from the southeastern historic city of Gyeongju It will show the compatible harmonious characteristics of Korean architecture that seamlessly blend into the surrounding nature the artist said  I hope the work remains there forever and is a reminder of Korea s cultural heritage the 84 year old said  Another famous Korean installation artist Kim Ku rim created a dreamy installation work Yin and Yang at the outdoor garden where a wooden boat carrying a boatful of flowers floats on the massive mirrored stainless plate that reflects the sky and clouds The reflection creates an impression as if the boat is flying in the sky fitting well with the heavenly theme  German artist Roger Rigorth created Wings on the water The white and light wings gently fluttering in the wind symbolize the history and soul of the Korean society American artist Steven Siegel s Suncheon Weave is his latest paper series dated back to 1990 According to the organizers the endless stacks of newspapers are meant to evoke geology time and the cycles of nature It is designed for visitors to walk around and inside the stacks  Co chairman Kim was cautiously optimistic about annualizing the festival saying the city has prepared this art festival for the past few years and that it will get more financial and logistical support if this year s first event goes smoothly  Annually 5 to 6 million people visit the city with a mere 280 000 population to see nature and the garden It is still too early to predict if this will become an annual event but we are definitely positive Kim said  German artist Roger Rigorth s Wings courtesy of the SEEAF Yonhap  American artist Steven Siegel s Suncheon Weave courtesy of the SEEAF Yonhap  Zero Gravity Big Drops by Oh Tae won courtesy of the SEEAF Yonhap  jaeyeon woo yna co kr  END
