2 atlases unveiled showing Japan s recognition of Dokdo as Korean territory  CHEONAN South Korea Oct 24 Yonhap A museum on the history of the Korean independence movement on Monday opened to the public two atlases showing Japan s recognition of Korea s easternmost islets of Dokdo as Korean territory  The atlases published by Japan obtained by a think tank of the Independence Hall of Korea are The Recent Japan Map which came out in 1912 for use by middle school students and specified Korea s sovereignty over the islets and a copy of The Asahi Picture News published in 1946  The Recent Japan Map a supplemented version with the latest materials based on a state run map compiled by the Japanese government in 1912 contains a map of the Korean Peninsula colored in red that reflected Japan s colonial rule of the peninsula at the time  Located southeast of Ulleung Island South Korea s North Gyeongsang Province and northwest of the Oki islands in Japan s Shimane Prefecture Dokdo consists of two small islets and a cluster of reefs Historians say that Japan incorporated Dokdo as part of Shimane in 1905 five years ahead of its 1910 45 colonization of the Korean Peninsula  This photo released by the Independence Hall of Korea on Oct 24 2015 shows The Recent Japan Map which came out in 1912 for use by middle school students and specified Korea s sovereignty over its easternmost islets of Dokdo Yonhap  In the same atlas a map of Japan s Chugoku and Shikoku areas shows the Oki islands are included in a square but Dokdo is outside of the boundary Yoon So young a researcher at the Independence Movement Research Institute said the atlas shows Japan had surely recognized Dokdo as Korean territory despite its 1905 incorporation of the islets into Shimane  The atlas is another example of many geographic textbooks of Japan s Meiji era 1868 1912 consistently inheriting the recognition of Dokdo as not being Japanese territory Yoon said  The Jan 5 1946 issue of The Asahi Picture News a graphic magazine published by the Asahi Shimbun newspaper from 1923 to 2000 carries a repainted world map detailing territories of the world after the World War II  A map on the newly borne Japan in the copy has a special mention that Japan s territory was newly decided based on the 1945 Potsdam Declaration that served as the basic terms of Japan s surrender in World War II  It carries the declaration s clause 8 that The terms of the Cairo Declaration shall be carried out and Japanese sovereignty shall be limited to the islands of Honshu Hokkaido Kyushu Shikoku and such minor islands as we determine excluding Dokdo from Japan s territory Yoon said  The unveiling of the atlases came one day before South Koreans hold various events to commemorate the fourth Day of Dokdo renewing their determination to defend Dokdo from Japan s sovereignty claim In 2010 some local municipalities and civic groups designated Oct 25 as the Day of Dokdo in a move viewed as bolstering the country s sovereignty over the East Sea islets  This photo released by the Independence Hall of Korea on Oct 24 2015 shows the cover of the January 5 1946 issue of The Asahi Picture News a graphic magazine published by the Asahi Shimbun newspaper Yonhap  namsh yna co kr  END
